We drove up from Virginia Beach. I was wanting fresh fish, and something other than fried. This place did not disappoint us. We were early so seating was immediate. Our waiter was very prompt, informative and engaging. The view of the ocean and pier was super. I ordered the swordfish, broiled. It came with a baked potato and seasonal veggies. My wife had crab cakes. Both were amazing. This place is a good value, IMHO.

My wife and I went there last night with my Father for dinner. When we arrived, we were greeted at the door by friendly staff of the restaurant. I was impressed since these days no one displays old school etiquette.  We ordered appetizers and she crab soup...the soup was delicious (although it needs a bit more crab in it). The calamari was tasty and not greasy like other places I've visited. The main course was OUTSTANDING...Halibut on a bed of risotto with pesto and fresh grape tomato's. I was totally pleased with the service from Tom, too. Professional waiter staff...not dinghy kids with piercings and bad attitudes. I'll be back soon.

Our Uncle used to take us here "in the old days".  We were pleased that it is still apparently very tightly run, and the staff is very attentive and friendly. The atmosphere is lovely, and many tables have nice views of the bay and pier. (ask for reservations?)

We made it easy on the waitress:  four fried seafood platters all around.  (not adventurous, I know, but this is what we came for : )    Everything was perfectly cooked, including the large scallops (which were about the best I've ever had).

There was a good selection of local and regional craft brews which we appreciated also.

One of us got dessert, the raspberry sorbet.  It was actually phenomenal, and its presentation was brilliant too.

It was nice to be back here after so long. Thanks Lynnhaven Fish House!

We had a mixed experience tonight. Most everything we had was great, and the server was wonderful. However, our entrees were sub-par. The Lobster, although tasty, was extremely tough; and the King Crab Legs, in the same respect, had a very dry rubbery texture. If you know anything about cooking seafood, both of these things happen when you overcook. We came at an off time, so I'm wondering if this is just a case of a bad chef. The appetizer, and all other food, were great... but when you spend $30 dollars for an entree, it better be perfect. I would honestly give this place one more shot to change my mind. In terms of value, it would have been justified if the food was flawless - but it could be considered a little pricey.

One of best seafood dining experience with an awesome ocean view,no less. The food is succulent.  Again, this is a great place for food & dining experience. The she crab soup is a fabulous starter. The street view of the restaurant does not match the indoor presentation...looks like a common fish camp from outside. I would go again for a special occasion. Food quality is comparable to Catch 31 in VIB but without modern ambiance.

Excellent food, good service, and with a lovely view. However, the manager could use some manners. Yelling at the staff right next to our table and only stopping to greet tables that appear to have "money" really isn't the way to go.
We had an amazing seafood meal. The fried shrimp were huge. The broiled flounder was cooked perfectly and the scallops were delicious. We had an excellent waitress. Definitely recommend dinner here.
One of if not the best place for local seafood in Virginia Beach! Everything I have ever tried has been top notch!  Thanks for the great meal and the oysters!
Great food. Service was also very good. All around a good experience. I recommend it.

I WANTED TO VOMIT! I filled up on hush puppies and their wonderful crabdip.  When my entree came out, I was a little full.  Yeah,  I thoughtvof doing the "super model" thing in order to eat more. The salmon was not over cooked. The texture of the breaded oysters and shrimp was perfect. My two guest also enjoyed their meals. Funny how I go here every New Years Eve...I guess they do it well. One other thing...everyone was incredibly friendly. Entering and exiting, the staff catered to us.

Never been to the restaurant but the attached fishing pier is great! They have everything you need to fish or crab there if you need it or bring your own gear and bait and just pay the small fee to access the pier for the day. Other people fishing/crabbing there are always really nice and the Fish & Game Warden even stopped and gave my boys some quick lessons on telling male/female crabs apart, when best to catch them, etc.

Restaurant is very dated to say the least. I've been an off and on guest for nearly 20 years and this place could use an update. First the decor is antiquated in terms of modern dining experiences. The waitress put a piece of paper on the table which listed the "catch of the day" which demonstrated that she didn't take the time to learn the fish. The paper was crumpled as it came out of her tattoo-laden arm. Next the bathroom was absolutely filthy. My wife exited the restroom with our daughter covered in soap and water due to the dysfunctional dispenser. There was toilet paper and feces on the floor. The food was super par to say the least. The only thing that has changed in the past two decades are the elevated prices on deep fried seafood. When you go, you pay a premium for the view, location, and name. The service, atmosphere, and quality of food are terrible.

Horrible customer service experience .My husnand and I attended a family wedding reception  dinner today 1/6/2017. The manger and hostess did not greet us upon arrival . On top of that the food was horrible.. What was crazy the had the nerve to rush us on the ordering meals and rush are check . Granted who know the restaurant close at 9pm. Funny they had no problem adding the gratuity 10% in check . How do you know the service was worth $10..  Well never again ...First and last time....

Will really miss this place when it closes on 12/31/2017.  Has always been the BEST Seafood in the area......with top notch She Crab soup and awesome homemade KeyLime pie!  Thanks for the memories Kris and team!

Classy establishment, friendly waiters and waitresses, excellent food and ambiance. A little pricey for a family of 3 or more but definitely worth the experience. Extending the menu selection a bit wouldn't hurt.

We never had such poor service and felt like we wasn't good enough to be there before. It was very busy so we sat at a table near the bar. The table beside us smelled of money and was very snotty. The waiter was bowing down to them but the man gripped about everything. The one lady did but not as much. However, he was on top of their every move. Working hard for that tip. As for Us, we asked for butter couldn't get that & we even had to wait for drink refills. It appeared he couldn't handle the work load and he was even sweating. Even the guy at the entrance didn't give two cents about us. We have never been so insulted in our lifes. We was spending money just like the other guests. To start i want to say the food was very good. We did not have an excellent experience in the area of customer service though. We went for the veteran's day event. It was advertised as a free meal for active duty, veterans, and gold star family members (parents and spouse). I am currently active duty and I planned to attend with my spouse, but on arrival when I asked, they said no just the servicemember gets a meal contrary to what was advertised on the giant sign I was standing right next to.  I appreciate when restaurants try to do something to give back, so I didn't press any further into it and I just ended up paying for the food. However, it makes a very bad impression to advertise one thing, but not follow through on the offer. If you only want to give this benefit to the serving member, advertise it that way. Besides that, the waiter for our table was very inattentive and failed to bring our drinks on time and didn't bring out the bread until we asked and even then we didn't get it until after our meal arrived. The place was not busy whatsoever at roughly 1 pm on a Sunday. They were open outside their normal hours for the veterans day event. The food was very good, but overall the experience was less than excellent and I was extremely underwhelmed. I would probably never return.

My wife and I went to M&M for our wedding anniversary, and we spared no expense. We purchased everything that we were interested in trying and eating and got a very nice bottle of wine on top of it. We had a great evening.

Unfortunately, that great evening turned sour when we got food poisoning from something in our meal (most likely from the undercooked bacon wrapped shrimp). Within two hours of leaving the establishment, we were both struck with stomach pain followed by vomiting and diarrhea. The demon was expelled, but We had not shared a single meal for three days before that evening so we know this is where it came from.

When we made a complaint, we were assured that it would be taken "very seriously" and there was no need to return our food as evidence. "That won't be necessary" we were told. So we threw it away. Why would we keep hundreds of dollars worth of possibly tainted food?

Expecting some kind of refund for our horrible experience, we were offered a non-committal 'dinner-on-us' with no specifics on what that entailed. My wife was understandably not interested in going back. We've called back a few times now and it has been several weeks, but we have not heard from anyone in management.

It seems they do not take such accusations very seriously at all, despite their initial claim. The only thing they've managed to do is drag this ordeal out so long that we've missed any opportunity we may have had to dispute the charges with our credit card company. We will never be going back to this, or any location of McCormick and Sh*ts.

We arrived and waited for several minutes as there wasn't a hostess at the front to greet guests.  Once seated, we waited for over 5 minutes for a server to approach is to see if we'd been helped.  It wasn't long till plates started piling up and not a server to be found again.  To make matters worse, we found out after being seated and told of the night's main items, ribs and steak.  If ribs and steak are the main meats, how do you run out at 7pm on a Thursday night?

Most items on the bar were fairly low as well.  While we were there, we saw at least 3 cooks standing around the back, 2-3 "managers" walking about and at least 5 or 6 servers.  As you can see in my attached photo, everyone just stood around ignoring the customers.  Our bottle of water at the table ran out early on after the initial fills, and we never were asked about a refill.  The table was bussed once during that hour.  Finally, we had to ask for our check after waiting for way too long to try and get anyone's attention.

All this would normally be overlooked, but there were only 6 seated tables inside and another 4 outside.  To have so many staff on hand not paying attention to tables as very poor customer service.  To run out of the main items on a slow night is very poor planning.  For the price, I can think of many other places to go instead.  Luckily, there are over 4,000 restaurants to choose from in Hampton Roads, so there's at least a silver lining!

I was not at all impressed with the Christmas Eve dinner buffet here. It was disappointing because I've looked forward to trying it out for years.

I spent over $200 for 4 people here and was not impressed with the selection, service, and food quality.

First, the salad bar was sad sad sad. Only 4 or so toppings to choose from, four salad dressings, and one type of not so fresh greens mix. There was a nearby "cheese bar" but I wouldn't call it that.... bunches of cheese on a tray that looked like from a Walmart platter with no plates or crackers or toppings is not that great.

The raw bar was probably the nicest element - a large bar with shrimp, salmon, and fresh raw oysters on ice. The shrimp and salmon were very good and my dad and boyfriend enjoyed the oysters, I don't eat them raw.

The hot food sections were equally disappointing. No steak, chicken, or prime rib. They did have some absolutely delicious and moist turkey at a carving station with gravy. That was very good. They had fatty beef and fatty brisket smothered in BBQ sauce. The sides were very dry roasted potatoes, bland corn with bacon pieces, Brussel sprouts and roasted bacon squash topped with a small piece of cheese and a cranberry. The squash was the standout. Nearby they had some rolls under a heat lamp - white and sweet potatoes. Often out of plates, no butter for a long period of time and when it did come out, it was frozen solid. A HUGE pet peeve of mine at a "fancy" place. Butter should never be frozen to be spread on bread. Ever. The rolls were hard and tasted like they were made a week ago, also, not warm. My boyfriend's 11-year old daughter commented they were like dog biscuits. I couldn't agree more.

The dessert bar was disappointing as well. I hoped for this to be the highlight. It wasn't. Several selections like cheesecake, bread pudding, chocolate cake, a peppermint swirl cake and Christmas cookies were "laid out" on a table outside the main buffet hall. Again, no plates, no refills of the items at the end of the night, they just ran out and it never got refilled.... the cakes were not moist and they were bland and tasteless with cheap whipped icing. Also, with no management the table was covered in crumbs and children and teens were sawing at cakes that were not pre-portioned or sliced to try to pick them up with tiny utensils. I even struggled... it was not well managed and was poor display and delivery of this.

The coffee and tea were good.

Service was OK. They were polite but continuously told us they were working Christmas Eve and were tired. We were also chastised for placing our own plates on the nearby tray to bus our tables despite the fact they weren't around to collect them and we needed to clear room.

Overall, not worth $200. I will not return.

I absolutely love the food here. You will find things that no other restaurant in the area offers. Fried green tomatoes, Corn nuggets, fried mushrooms etc. They aren't your typical fried mushrooms, they are fresh with very little breading, more like a tempura batter, excellent!  Fried green tomatoes are also lightly breaded and melt in your mouth, but the corn nuggets - - - I've never had them anywhere else, they are the food that you go home and dream about for days! You have to ask them to bring you a side of their homemade ranch dressing and their homemade roumalaide sauce for dipping.. unbelievably delicious!! The homemade yams are almost as good as my moms and that is saying something ! The barbeque fries are loaded with pulled pork, these are all considered appetizers and sides but I am telling you if you order any of the 3 items listed above and  order a side of yams or barbeque fries you will not be able to finish it all. I love the food here. I would've given 5 stars but the server is a little strange, sometimes she barely talks and acts like you are asking for the world when you request ranch or roumalaide and other times she hovers and talks you to death. Also the iced tea is over priced at $3 a glass. Come for the food, not the tea or service, or call ahead and get it to go, yummy stuff.. My entire family loves it!

This place is a hidden gem ("hidden" on the far, back corner of the strip mall).

(1) Great atmosphere ... good background music, plenty of TVs that carry the games - and if you want to hear the TV, the bartender/waitress will give you a small wireless speaker so you can hear the play-by-play w/o disturbing others!

(2) Very reasonable prices.

(3) Large & tasty oysters (I think my buddy downed at least two dozen).

(4) A versatile menu that can satisfy landlubbers like myself (generous-sized salads that you can substitute turkey & ham for seafood, burgers, steak, grilled chicken, etc.). If you have a non-seafood eater in your group, they don't have to sacrifice so the rest of your party can enjoy their seafood!

(5) One of my favorites: the homemade hush puppies by the basket!

(6) Oh, I almost forgot ... happy hour appetizer specials (even on the weekend).

Lauren, the bar tender, was sociable and very attentive - our glasses/mugs were never empty.  She's a great asset to this establishment.

Awful Arthur's may have become my local favorite spot to hang-out, eat great food, and watch the ball games!

I am so happy there is a place like this close by. The atmosphere is relaxed but done very well. The food is delicious and reasonably priced. It is like an unpretentious seafood restaurant that you'd find in a beach town. If you want non-seafood, they have some good options. Finally, they have a substantial draught menu of local beers along with a a good selection of wine and liquors.

Came in on a Friday night @ 7:30. Not one other customer was in the place. Why? I brought a group of 8 with me and when walking up to the bar, under her breath, one of my group said ‚ÄúI feel sorry for them‚Äù. The rude bartender berated my guest by saying ‚Äúdon‚Äôt feel sorry for me with your Drunken whisper‚Äù. We were not drunk, we went here to get drinks not because we had been drinking. By the looks of things, this place is on the way out. I wish there was some presence of management or feeling that our business was wanted. I don‚Äôt think it is, sadly.

To the management:

I admire the challenge of being in such a location yet trying to remain prosperous. It‚Äôs difficult at this location. Here are my suggestions if you don‚Äôt want to close your door (which by the looks of the thin crowd when we visit, this is near).

1) Take care of your customers. I have never once had a manager or someone in a leadership role come over to our table and ask hour our meal was. It‚Äôs a small place and I don‚Äôt believe I even know what the owner looks like, and I‚Äôve been her 5-10 times.

2) For the love of GOD, reduce your prices. The environment is not 4-5 star so you shouldn‚Äôt be charging $28 for 1lb of crab legs that are no better than Publix grocery. Although they are decent, that‚Äôs a travesty.

I‚Äôd like to come back and I‚Äôm sure others will agree that if these 2 points were addressed than you would start to see pickup. I‚Äôm sure this is easier said than done(well #2 at least), but please try. Thanks!!

Wednesdays are a real treat here for Happy Hour and Dinner, with Steve Bassett playing alternately between this location or Midlothian.  We've never had anything but a good time with friends and enjoying delicious seafood.  Actually any day or evening is a good experience at Awful Arthur's!

Staff treats you like family. Food is always delicious and if there‚Äôs ever a tiny mistake they‚Äôre more than happy to adjust anything you‚Äôd like. The she crab soup is my favorite and the tuna is consistently perfect.

Amazing food for starts, went for mother's day and had an awesome experience. Excellent wine paired with insanely delicious food and extremely attentive staff, made it a mother's day to remember. Will more than consider for future anniversaries with my wife.

This may be about as perfect of a date night as you can get. They are located in a very quiet area. They have their own parking lot for their customers only. There's not a lot a seating inside and this is one of the few places we've been that's actually pretty quiet while you eat. You can have a good conversation! We started with the bread service and two appetizers, the beet salad and their crab bisque. The bread was fantastic, nice crust good flavor and was accompanied by oil and balsamic. The salad was good and the crab bisque was as good as we've ever eaten. it was crab and nearly every bite and sometimes the crab would be larger than the spoon. Absolutely decadent. For a main course, we ordered the lollipop lamb chops and the beef Wellington. The lollipop lamb chops and the beef Wellington were both ordered mid rare and they both came exactly as ordered! Everything was well seasoned including the vegetables and mashed potatoes. It's rare these days to find a chef that actually seasons and tests before serving. Everything we put in our mouth was first class and we will definitely be back. Get your honey and get to Voila. You will definitely score some points!

Amazing service, outstanding meal, and lovely atmosphere. Wine list has some great selections and the cocktails are extremely well executed. We can't wait to go back - been dreaming about the french onion soup!!
We didn't have a reservation but were seated before the res. showed up. The beef wellington was amazing but the lamp chops are hands down the best I've had. Can't wait to go back!

Decided to go here for an anniversary dinner. They have there own parking lot onsite, eliminating a potential problem in this neighborhood. Our server was friendly, knowledgeable, and helpful without being overbearing. They have a good selection of classic bar drinks. We started with salad and escargot, and had steak and seafood entrees. Everything looked and tasted great. We would recommend this place to anyone.
Straight up amazing. Everything that we had for dinner was top notch. We will definitely be returning. This is a must try in Norfolk.

If we could give 10 stars, I would find a way to try and give 20 more. Wow! Absolutely stunning!!! From the minute I called to make Valentines Day reservations 3 months ago and was told it was made too early to make reservations, I set it on my calender to make reservations on tge earliest day possible the minute they opened. Due to how stunning the woman who answered the phone was and so kind was on the initial call was. The same lady answered on the second time yet again and was so lovely and so professional that I was already in without even ever had the food. My fiance has always wanted a Beef Wellington so after googling places to have one I found this hidden gem. The lady was kind enough to tell me they would not be serving it on Valentines Day due to its popularity so I made reservations on 2/13. In my 41 years of living in Hampton Roads and being one to enjoy fine dining, I have NEVER experienced such excellent food and service and a perfectly spread and well timed out dinner from appetizer to dessert. I wanted scallops and risotto and then the special was Rockfish and risotto and I asked to not even tell me what the price would be and see if I could have both protiens over risotto and they made it happen. It's now named "Ed over a bed of Risotto" or how ever you would say it in French. LOL. If you have never been here you must go! Thank you so much to our server, chef and entire staff for making such an amazing Valentines after such a tough year with Covid. 5 Star experience from beggining to end. Thank you all and especially our server whom I am sorry we didn't get you're name because we were so engulfed by our total experience. I'm not paid to make this review, but word of mouth is what makes this world go round and this Precious Gem of a restaurant deserves it. Thanks again!
Wonderful food, service and atmosphere! Definitely worth another visit!

Quaint, small intimate restaurant with some of the best food I have had in quite a long time. I do plan on going back again. I had planned on having the beef wellington but changed my mind and had the pork shoulder with escargot for an appetizer and an exceptional chocolate mousse for dessert I had planned on having the beef wellington but changed my mind.  EVERYTHING was delicious.  Some excellent jazz playing in the background.

Fantastic. I took my wife for dinner and we started with the escargot. The snails were tender, not rubbery, and the flavor was nice. I ordered some wine and lamb, and my wife got the duck. Both were delicious, although I have to say, the duck offered more in flavor and overall enjoyability, probably due to the port reduction. Quiet little restaurant, very cozy, with unique decor that gives the restaurant space a twist, without being too out of place. Perfect date night. (It also started raining while we were eating which added a relaxing ambience.)

Always a delightful dining experience. We we're 2 couples all ordering different entrees. We all enjoyed our dinners. Service was lovely & ambience
always charming.

The service and the wine we're superb.  The food was excellent but not special, except for the lemon sherbert for dessert.  This said it used real lemons and it did!  My experience had previously been that lemon ices were less than the "real" taste in homemade lemonade, but this time I obtained the real thing.  And the ambiance was fine.

Love this place, their she-crab soup is probably THE best I've ever had. It's a nice, small restaurant that's a little more high-end, waiters are fantastic, food is delicious. You'd not go wrong taking a date here.

Our 4th visit.  Very tasty, beautifully presented cuisine.  Reasonably priced. Many good wines available by the glass. Tables are very tightly packed into an interestingly decorated, albeit small, dining area: too close to neighboring tables to be called considered intimate/romantic dining, but otherwise very pleasant ambience.
Charming and delicious restaurant. I had perfectly cooked scallops on Carolina rice and peas- just divine.
As always, this wonderful international Restaurant creates delicious dishes, served by knowledgeable and attentive service. Try it!
You are in a beautiful dining room being served like you are royalty. The food is wonderful. The family will go if we feel like we're dinning in Paris. So wonderful to go.

This is a great little place to have dinner (I'm not sure if they are open during the day for lunch).  The atmosphere is nice, quiet and can be intimate for a first date because of the smaller restaurant size. I love the 19th century stone road this restaurant sits on (the street is original stone from the 1800's). Voila is a smaller restaurant (about 12-15 tables), with a small bar and the local fish served is delivered daily from George's Seafood (so you know the fish is fresh and great quality). The owner and staff are wonderful people! Try Viola out today for a quiet dinning experience outside downtown Norfolk.

Wonderful dinner!
I had lamb chops and they were very nice. Others had rockfish and they were pleased as well. The deserts were good too.

This place is very intimate and decorated with Vintage Theater posters. Soothing music playing in the background quiet conversation  between people. A well-stocked bar  with a lovely selection of  wine and hard alcohol . Had a whiskey sour that was made just right. Wonderful  service without being too overbearing but attentive. The food is absolutely to die for. Being able to taste every intricate spice used with all the flavor to savor. The crab bisque is by far the best I've had in Virginia Beach, everywhere else drowns it with too much Sherry.  The duck was made so tender and moist with the skin perfectly crisp. Their in-house made chocolate mousse made my mouth water. The creme brulee caramelized top was cooked just right to have the right amount of smoky taste the didn't overpower it. The lemon sherbet sorbet had a wonderful sweet tart that gave me a good Zing. Everything about this place I absolutely adored I look forward to eating here again.

Wow....not even sure how to start this review. We dined here for the first time tonight. The setting was intimate and pleasing to the eye. The rich earth tones and understated elegance works very well together. We ordered one of the three-course meals. From the first sip of the flavorful, savory french onion soup thru the perfectly prepared final dish, it was all ahhmazing! The staff was attentive and genuinely friendly. The various dishes were served in a timely fashion. No sooner were you finishing one dish, the next course was on its way. Our dessert was packed to go and traveled quite well I must say...lol. Kudos Chef Robinson and your outstanding team!! We will see you all again!

Overall this place is pretty good. I think my biggest complaint is just a price. I know it's supposed to be a high-class and upscale place, but it just seems unnecessarily expensive. Example or cocktails or $12 each don't really see why they couldn't be $10. It's a very nice place but be prepared to drop quite a bit to have an enjoyable meal. The desert are comically small. Do not get those earn! It is not worth it.

Amazing food.  I am in the military and I have been eating in restaurants around the world and this place became one of my three best restaurants.  The other two are in Dubai and New York.  I strongly recommend this place to anyone who believes food is art.

Loved the food and appletizers. We (group of six)enjoyed the crab appletizer and beef Wellington's. The atmosphere is quaint and the staff are friendly and attentive. I would recommend trying out this restaurant.

Thought this would be a nice place to take my wife for her birthday dinner but we ended up leaving rather quickly due to how uncomfortable we were.  It's too bad really wanted to like this place.

Will never return to this location.  Owner is rude and if I didn't know any better racist. Also she went ahead to say something completely racist.   Definitely very rude and I will be reporting them to BBB

This is one of my favorite restaurants in Norfolk. Amazing food and ambiance. Highly recommend.

It is a small quaint establishment. With excellent decor and lighting. The service was top notch. The waiter was well versed in proper etiquette. Man, oh man, the Tradewinds restaurant! Just mentioning it my taste buds go all crazy. I don't know the chef's name but he must be a magician in the kitchen. I dinned every night during my 4 night stay at Virginia Beach Resort recently, and it was not even a weekend when you'd think they'll go all out on having the best service. It was a feast on my plate every night. Well worth the time, money and all that view- MAGNIFICENT. My hostess, the restaurant manager that stopped to ask how we were doing, my server's excellent tableside manners and that unparallelled view of the sunset over the Chesapeake Bay Bridge- OMG. If you're ever down in Virginia Beach, DO make the effort and go do Tradewinds- you won't regret it. Their best kept secret is that every Wednesday night they have their own version of Yo Yo Ma, going by the name of Lewis McGehee, that makes your bones melt along with your taste buds. I'm far from a romantic but give me a she-crab soup + a great sunset+ wonderful music and it can't ever spell anything better than Tradewinds restaurant at the Virginia Beach Resort Hotel and Conference Center. If you've never been there you've never seen Virginia Beach at its best.

Nothing like finding one of the biggest Mexican seafood restaurant names from Houston so far north.  For those that know how a Saturday morning feels after a late Friday night...this place made it all better.

I was skeptical at first.  The ones in Houston are mainly off main thoroughfares, i.e. I-45, and you CANNOT miss them with those gi-normous signs.  This one is nowhere near the grandeur of the other 11-or-so locations and quite quaint actually.  Very small footprint with a more modest venue.

It wasn't bustling during lunch hour when we walked in so the skepticism grew twice-fold.  It was wife/kid in tow and the bar was full!  No one sitting at the tables.  One thing that verified within 10 seconds of walking was that something was good at this joint.

We have been seeking our go-to Mexican, not Mexi-dorean as is commonplace here, for over a year now.  El Paso is ok but just melting cheese on my burrito doesn't make it "authentic".  We have tried Tacos Moya and were treated so horrible that by principle can't go back.

Back to this joint...the hostess essentially let us sit wherever we wanted being that nobody cared for a non-bar seat.  We were cool with that and bee-lined to a booth just past a small Banda platform.  Must have a karaoke or actual live music on occasion.  THE Selena looked down at me as I sat down.

Drinks? Micheladas, please!  My friends, if you're still with me, this was the first time I poured my own beer into the Michelada mix at a restaurant.  Is it a big deal?  Of course it is.  Could have used a few ice cubes but the heat, lime, saltiness and powdered rim was there on a chilled mug that my thirst desired.
Salsa was good also. Not just blended tomato with no salt.

Food?  Coktel "Vuelve a la Vida" please!  I could taste the freshness as I inhaled it.  The hint of ketchup mixed with Valentina and  each chilled bite of shrimp, squid, oyster and pico made me reminisce of the times I would frequent my go-to restaurants.

Oh, and the kid approves also.  She had a quesadilla with fajita.  She doesn't like anything interrupting her "tortilla and cheese" but she...ate...the...whole...thing. As well as most of her rice and beans.  She always eats the chips but she ate most of those, too.

As we waited two other families came in with infants.  One was a white couple. Let's not complicate an observation as I simply state it because I feel it should be mentioned in today's frame of strife with the Hispanic population.  To add to this, he ordered a fajita entree and it came out with the signature sizzling and aroma of grilled veggies that makes it even more appetizing. He was not phased even with him handling the baby inches from it.  Mexican-restaurant veterans they were!

Some shortcomings that were minor we overlooked with quality of our food. Cokteles normally come with saltines and lime.  Maybe she was new?  We didn't bother her because again it was a full bar and only two servers.

Will visit again.  Maybe even tomorrow to try those fajitas.
Delicious food and great service. Monica is always so friendly and efficient. If ever in the neighborhood and want to try authentic Mexican seafood cuisine give it a try.

The Seviche Tostada was a meal in itself,  and the Whole  Fried Red Snapper with Octopus, Mussels,  Shrimp and Squid with Onions and Peppers  Fried Rice and French Fries was a steal....Best meal I've had in years ,  This is hidden gem in the Manassas/Centerville area...

Since the evening was going to be gorgeous and being that it was Saturday, figured it would be prudent to make a reservation.  Upon arrival, I was quickly greeted by the manager. She made us feel welcomed and immediately pointed out that we will be seated shortly. I requested if we could have an outside seating. She politely replied that she will try to accommodate our request to the best of her abilities - she was not only able to seat us outside, but we had a good view of the establishment and the vicinity surrounding us from where we sat.

Waitress was friendly. She asked what we would like to have for drinks,  we made an order and I replied that we still needed to look over the menu. While we're looking over the menu, we felt something sticking to BOTH of our menus. Not sure whether the remnants of sashimi were already laying on the table and stuck to our menus, or the waitress didn't cleaned them properly - no matter how you slice it, it's just not a good look.

We started out with Spicy Turn Rolls and Canary Island Rolls. Sushi arrived in relatively short time. The presentation was impeccable, but I wish I could say the same about about the taste. I know I enjoy my food spicy, and I'm fully aware when it says spicy, that it's made spicy for the general consumption. However,  I did not feel a single pinch of spice which my date can attest to :)  The rolls tasted gamy and just not up to the level the restaurant has lived up to in the past. Maybe the Sushi Chef wasn't having a good day, or today's delivery just wasn't the freshest - who knows.

On to my entree, the OB Fish Tacos. Lets just say the establishment was able to redeem itself. The fish was crispy with just the right amount of batter. The cilantro and avocado were fresh and the garlic aioli was fantastic.

I really enjoyed the ambiance they've created with number of actual fish tanks spread throughout the entire restaurant, with unique blend of exterior and interior seating setup. On the contrary, finding the restrooms were reminiscent of playing a game of finding 'The Secret Door' - I guess that's why the waitress stood there expecting us to ask about the restrooms, based on how it quickly it rolled out of her tongue, "I can help you find where the restrooms are" :)

I will go there again, but they need to work little bit on cleanliness and maybe the sushi should live up the establishment's name as it has in the past.

AMAZING! Wonderful decor and atmosphere. Great Staff and great food! I highly recommend the Sriracha Tuna Roll!  The shrimp lettuce wraps were amazing as well, however, the sushi takes the cake for me!
Fish tacos were good. Good beer selection. Sushi boats are fun and tasty.

Went for a date night, atmosphere is nice, the boats are an interesting touch.

Staff is average, fish tanks are also a cool touch. Ordered appetizers which came out Luke warm. The actually taste wasn't bad for calamari, little more spice would've been good.

Wife ordered salmon which was a little fishy, but overall not terrible.

My food surf and turf well that was kinda terrible. Steak was cold, over cooked, just like the lobster. The mash was good.

Overall it was a good first date place or give it a try. Other than that there are other places in the area that are better.

This is such a neat restaurant! The aquarium is beautiful and the moat is cool. It's like a lazy river of sushi!
I had the poke, which was quite good. I also enjoyed the Maryland roll, but found it was a bit salty. My friend liked the Caribbean roll.
The beer selection was very nice and well priced, and the happy hour seems great.

My only issue is that they talk about fishing sustainably, but they fly the fish in from Hawaii on pretty much a daily basis. Not very environmentally responsible. Just something to think about.

Staff is friendly and helpful but they don't quite have a routine down. Had the Surf and Turf but it was only ok. The steak wasn't seasoned well and the potatoes tasted like they were out of a box. However, the lobster was seasoned beautifully. Husband had the Ramon bar and found lots of things he liked. He enjoys spicy and was very happy. Thinking that this would be a great place for the sushi and Ramon but not necessarily the main dishes. However, this was only our first visit so time will only tell.

Second visit, not as great as the first. Service was surprisingly slow, despite it not being that busy (there were several tables empty). The food was good but took a long time to be delivered (the appetizer itself took over 30 minutes to arrive). Also, the sushi river was never refilled the entire time we were there - the same empty boats circled around and around repeatedly. Not sure what happened. Will try again and hope for the best.

Have great rewards for kids who finish the scavenger hunt.

It's a shame that a beautiful restaurant just gave me a terrible dining experience. I waited 45 minutes for a grilled fish that was undercooked to the point it was difficult to cut. They took it to the kitchen and when they brought me another one it was half the size. I really didn't complain because I was super hungry. But then my boyfriend noticed it and said that his burger was burned on one side.
Server came to the table to apologize and said the dessert was on them. But then he never came back to the table for 20 minutes. We had to stop him to ask for the check and then the manager came to ask how was our dinner. I almost said terrible, but my boyfriend answered fine quickly because he just wanted to get out of there. I did too. So disappointed because I had high expectations.

My bookclub met here and the following week we celebrated my birthday. They have great food, excellent service, and beautiful decor. I love the fish tanks, and the private dining room made me feel like a VIP.

Service was very attentive and the conveyor belt sushi was pretty good.  The unique rolls they have look good and the Rastafarian Roll we had was a good chance from the usual.  The ramen bar was only okay.

We waited 20 minutes for a table outside that was open the entire 20 minute wait. The waiter was amazing, but the food was extremely bland. Fish tacos were not seasoned. None of the food seemed to be seasoned at all. The short island iced tea claims to have multiple liquors in it, but you could get away with drinking that at rehab. Reviewing after my second visit. Overall an enjoyable atmosphere with two large fish tanks filled with tropical fish and two rivers of sushi floating on boats to grab and eat.

Prices are a bit high for the portions for both appetizers and sushi. Same for the regatta style sushi boats, the bill will sneak up on you.

Ramen bar looks like the best bang for your buck at $5 a bowl, but note no meat available. Calamari was better than expected and served with mango. The chicken island sandwich had an aioli that wasn't great and a sauce for the fries that was awful. The sandwich was overall very tasty.

The manager has checked in each visit to ensure guests are enjoying the trip. I'll go back a 3rd time to try more items on the menu.

Long waits, and pricey food for an "eh, it was alright" experience. The mediterranean chicken I got seemed bland. Management needs to hire more wait staff or look into optimizing efficiency and time in the kitchen.

the sushi that floated around the tank was obviously frozen and still thawing. it was incredibly slimy and oily. safeway sushi is better tasting than ocean blue. the ramen bar was disappointing to say the least. there were two different types of broth offered and they both tasted like they just threw all their bouillon cubes into a pot of water. the "toppings" were a bit random and lacking. only real upside was that the staff were very polite, and ready to serve our every need. even with that factor, i am never coming back here again.

Went with some co-workers to try it out for a lunch spot. The ramen was good and I like the idea of a ramen bar, but the sushi was meh and all kinda tasted the same. Service was good and the "sushi regatta" is a novel sight.

Maybe it's because we went on a day after a holiday;  however, the boats were severly lacking in their offerings.  There was no eel nor something as simple as a Philadelphia roll coming around.

The ramen soup base was extremely bland and unsatisfying.  The best thing of the whole meal was my child's mac-n-cheese.

Postives?  They have a lovely fish tank, friendly staff and wonderful atmosphere...but if the food isn't there or any good, who's going back?

Another suggestion is to stop using paper table cloth on top of the cotton kind. It left my partner with finger and arm paper cuts. Small flaws that can easily be fixed.

I had a long day of work, and wanted to relax with a good meal. I haven't been to  Bonefish in a long time, many years, and decided to stop by this BoneFish for a meal. The young waiter (unfortunately, I didn't get his name), was so helpful and friendly. The restaurant wasn't busy, with several patrons in addition to me sitting in the dining room. My waiter was very attentive. He made recommendations, and came back to check on me. I ordered the mussel appetizer, and he suggested that I dip the bread into the broth, and it was delicious. He had short conversation with me about my meal, and since I was dining alone, it was nice to have a good conversation with my meal, and at the same time, my waiter knew to leave me alone so that I can enjoy my food. The food was pretty good, but it was on the lighter side when it comes to salt. I don't eat a lot of salt, and prefer my food very lightly salted, but the seabass had very little salt. I prefer it had a little more, and I don't like adding salt to my meal once it has been served unless it needs it badly. I ate it as it. The sauteed spinach was delicious and so was the asparagus. I will come back again and try something different.

Wife and I were in the mood for seafood and we had a coupon to get an entree free with the purchase of an entree.  While we've been to the Centreville location several times, this was our first visit to the Fairfax one.

Everything was delicious!  We ordered a watermelon martini (for the wife) and it was actually really good!  If I'm going to drink a foo-foo drink, I at least want to taste the advertised fruit instead of pure sugar, and this drink was a perfect blend of watermelon with a slight hint of alcohol.

The fresh baked bread is amazing. Crisp on the outside, warm and soft on the inside...talk about self control to not eat everything in one gulp!  We ordered the sashimi appetizer and were pleasantly surprised with the size of the dish.  It was a great plate of tuna, greens and siracha drizzle.

My wife ordered the scallops and I ordered the crusted haddock.  Both dishes were perfectly cooked, flavorful and filling.  The thing I appreciate is that there are plenty of wild caught fish to choose from with only a couple fish being farm raised.  There aren't many places that offer such a wide variety of seafood choices, and the fact that Bonefish is aware of how much better wild caught fish is makes me have it at the top of my seafood list!

I don't do many chain type restaurants in the city but when you are in suburbia it seems like that is all there is. BoneFish is a popular restaurant in the neighborhood so we decided to try it.

6pm - Saturday night and it was packed. There was a line of people waiting. We were given one of those square blinking lights gadget standard with a lot of the chain restaurants.

It was nice they had servers going around with tasting while the people waited. Nice touch.

6:45pm- Gadget lights up. The hostess said it would just take a few minutes as our table was getting ready.

7:00pm - Seated and a very friendly server went through the menu with us. We started with the Cerviche  and Singapore Calamari. I would have to say the cerviche had a nice tartness and was pretty good. The calamari was a bit over fried and I didn't really like the sweet dipping sauce that came with it.

7:30pm - The entrees came out, the Fish and Chips, the grilled scallops and shrimp and grilled Grouper. All the seafood that came out seem fresh. The sauces that were recommended to try was also okay. I don't know if it really added any flavor to the dishes.  I've had better Fish & Chips. Everything was cooked nicely and it tasted perfectly fine. It tasted like a chain restaurant pumping out food. The standards were good but not very exciting. It wasn't a bad meal but then it wasn't a memorable meal.

8:30pm - We decided to skip desert and asked for the bill.

8:45pm - Out the door. While the service was exemplary and the food fresh but middling. It follows the tried and true formula of chain restaurants. Consistent food and service but what it lacks is the depth.

I've been a patron of Sakura for twenty years. I lived in MD and I was thrilled when they opened a location in Loudoun. Before, i travelled to Tysons. I've tried many of the local steakhouses but Sakura is consistent with quality and taste. I love this place.

I brought my two young sons here to try their first Japanese food.  We sat at a regular table (not a grill table) because I just bought them some maki sushi and tempura. The four year old did not like the maki, but the ten year old enjoyed it. (I didn't dare tell him what "unagi" is until after we had left.) Both children loved the tempura.
The staff was friendly and helpful, especially with the children. Without asking, the server brought small plastic "hinges" for the children's chopsticks that allowed them to eat more easily. After the meal, our server brought out to-go cups for the kids' sodas, again, without having to be asked.
Both children told me that they wanted to go back some time to eat at a grill table and watch the show.

We used to be regulars. But honestly I'm not sure anymore. They decided to start charging an outrageous price for yum yum sauce if you want more than 2 tiny cups with the meal. But fine, whatever ill pay even though the cost is a bit much. But the breaking point is when I spend $60 on a meal for 2, get one meal (steak and chicken ordered the steak  medium well) and get the other meal new York steak ordered medium RARE, and BOTH were cooked well done. Way to ruin a steak. Idk if they're getting laY since its take out only and they tie the bags around the boxes very tight so people can't check their food. But if I'm paying this much I expect my food to be cooked correctly. This isnt tgi fridays cheap food. They should not be way over cooking my food. There's a huge difference between medium rare and well done. So I ate my over cooked food and decided not to be back to this location. It was a shame because before the shut down we ordered take out from there about twice a month, sometimes more.
